1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,360
Well, let's dive straight into this in-depth look and discover the economic origins

2
00:00:05,360 --> 00:00:09,200
of one of the most notorious criminal organizations in history.

3
00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:14,919
It's an amazing story, strictly based on data, and I assure you it will radically change

4
00:00:14,919 --> 00:00:18,320
the perspective on historical events that we often take somewhat for granted.

5
00:00:18,320 --> 00:00:23,080
Let's start with a paradox that really makes you think, an enigma that economists call

6
00:00:23,080 --> 00:00:25,080
the resource curse.

7
00:00:25,160 --> 00:00:29,200
Have you ever wondered why immense natural resources bring incredible wealth

8
00:00:29,200 --> 00:00:33,960
in nations like Norway, for example, while in other regions they literally generate

9
00:00:33,960 --> 00:00:35,800
only corruption and conflicts?

10
00:00:35,800 --> 00:00:40,480
Well, to understand it, we will explore a fascinating historical mystery that leads us straight to Italy

11
00:00:40,480 --> 00:00:43,600
of the 19th century and, more precisely, to Sicily.

12
00:00:43,600 --> 00:00:49,799
Now, first of all, we need to reset and rethink the Mafia in purely

13
00:00:49,799 --> 00:00:52,960
economic terms, leaving behind movie clichés.

14
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:57,200
The data tells us that, historically, the Mafia was not just a group of violent

15
00:00:57,200 --> 00:01:02,560
criminals, but rather a real opportunistic industry; that is, they provided a

16
00:01:02,560 --> 00:01:07,000
private protection service in a market where the state was, in fact, absent.

17
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:10,519
Part one: the power vacuum in Sicily.

18
00:01:10,519 --> 00:01:14,799
In short, how was this very strange protection market created?

19
00:01:14,799 --> 00:01:18,920
The essential starting point is that weak public institutions are the absolute

20
00:01:18,920 --> 00:01:22,000
fertile ground for the resource curse.

21
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:28,040
It all began in 1806, when the Bourbons moved to Palermo; a few years later, in 1812,

22
00:01:28,040 --> 00:01:32,519
the formal abolition of feudalism disrupted centuries of power balance, eventually

23
00:01:32,519 --> 00:01:39,200
leading to the total collapse of the Bourbon kingdom in 1861. The practical effect: a disastrous

24
00:01:39,200 --> 00:01:41,359
and immense power vacuum.

25
00:01:41,359 --> 00:01:44,040
No one enforced the law, no one defended property.

26
00:01:44,040 --> 00:01:46,760
And what was the result of this state collapse?

27
00:01:47,480 --> 00:01:53,960
An intellectual of the time, Leopoldo Franchetti, in 1876, coined a brilliant expression.

28
00:01:53,960 --> 00:01:57,400
He spoke of a democratization of violence.

29
00:01:57,400 --> 00:01:58,960
Think about it for a moment.

30
00:01:58,960 --> 00:02:05,840
Suddenly, there was a disproportionate supply of former soldiers, armed guards, and even former convicts

31
00:02:05,840 --> 00:02:09,000
who previously worked for the barons and were now unemployed.

32
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:15,040
An immense workforce out on the streets, but perfectly specialized in just one thing:

33
00:02:15,040 --> 00:02:16,640
the use of force.

34
00:02:16,680 --> 00:02:20,520
Part 2: the great sulfur boom.

35
00:02:20,520 --> 00:02:25,600
And here, the story becomes explosive, because that huge availability of armed men

36
00:02:25,600 --> 00:02:29,320
collided with a completely unexpected economic shock.

37
00:02:29,320 --> 00:02:32,320
Look at the striking curve of this historical data.

38
00:02:32,320 --> 00:02:35,080
There was an incredible surge in exports.

39
00:02:35,080 --> 00:02:40,600
We're talking about an annual growth rate of 9% between the 1830s and 1850s.

40
00:02:40,600 --> 00:02:45,360
Sulfur, out of nowhere, became the most precious export commodity of all.

41
00:02:45,400 --> 00:02:48,080
But why this explosion in demand?

42
00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:54,280
Well, the world was in the middle of the Industrial Revolution and was in desperate need of this material.

43
00:02:54,280 --> 00:02:59,560
Sulfur was an absolutely crucial ingredient for the French and British chemical industries,

44
00:02:59,560 --> 00:03:04,440
which were growing immensely, not to mention it was needed for gunpowder.

45
00:03:04,440 --> 00:03:08,560
And, last but not least, it became fundamental in agriculture as a fungicide.

46
00:03:08,560 --> 00:03:12,760
Obviously, with the staggering increase in the value of sulfur, the value of protecting

47
00:03:12,759 --> 00:03:15,879
the sites where it was extracted also skyrocketed.

48
00:03:15,879 --> 00:03:19,399
Do you want to understand the true proportions of this global madness?

49
00:03:19,399 --> 00:03:23,000
I'll give you just one number: 83%.

50
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:29,879
By 1893, Sicily was not just a major producer; it had an almost total monopoly.

51
00:03:29,879 --> 00:03:34,280
It extracted up to 83% of all the world's sulfur.

52
00:03:34,280 --> 00:03:36,840
We're talking about unimaginable wealth,

53
00:03:36,840 --> 00:03:40,479
falling upon a territory practically devoid of state control.

54
00:03:40,479 --> 00:03:41,599
Part 3

55
00:03:41,680 --> 00:03:43,919
The Protection Market

56
00:03:43,919 --> 00:03:48,159
So, what happens when an army of violent, unemployed men

57
00:03:48,159 --> 00:03:52,639
meets a very high demand to protect incredibly profitable mines

58
00:03:52,639 --> 00:03:54,280
that are not defended by the state?

59
00:03:54,280 --> 00:03:55,240
Exactly.

60
00:03:55,240 --> 00:03:58,079
A flourishing protection market was born.

61
00:03:58,079 --> 00:04:02,719
If we look at this historical map, drawn by Officer Antonino Cutrera in 1900,

62
00:04:02,719 --> 00:04:07,599
we immediately notice how the darker regions, indicating a high concentration of early Mafia activities,

63
00:04:07,599 --> 00:04:12,000
are grouped almost entirely in the western and southern parts of the island.

64
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:15,479
Now, the thing that will leave you speechless is this.

65
00:04:15,479 --> 00:04:22,000
By overlaying the map of the distribution of sulfur mines from 1886—boom—

66
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:25,319
a staggering visual coincidence emerges.

67
00:04:25,319 --> 00:04:31,600
There is an undeniable, perfect overlap between the districts rich in deposits, in dark blue,

68
00:04:31,600 --> 00:04:35,199
and the territories in which the historical Mafia took root.

69
00:04:35,240 --> 00:04:40,479
And if the map isn't enough, historical data confirms everything crystal clearly.

70
00:04:40,479 --> 00:04:46,279
Take the famous trial of the so-called "Brotherhood of Favara" in 1883.

71
00:04:46,279 --> 00:04:50,199
Out of 107 convicted Mafia affiliates, guess what?

72
00:04:50,199 --> 00:04:55,319
No less than 72 were employed at various levels in the sulfur industry itself.

73
00:04:55,319 --> 00:05:03,039
It is concrete proof on the ground of the unbreakable link between mining and the emergence of organized violence.

74
00:05:03,039 --> 00:05:04,240
Part 4.

75
00:05:04,280 --> 00:05:06,000
Myth vs. Reality.

76
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:10,840
At this point, it is absolutely necessary to debunk a giant myth.

77
00:05:10,840 --> 00:05:17,560
It's often said that the citrus industry—the famous lemons—was the true cause of the Mafia's rise,

78
00:05:17,560 --> 00:05:20,879
but the data tells us otherwise, dismantling this theory.

79
00:05:20,879 --> 00:05:24,400
True, lemons were mass-cultivated around Palermo,

80
00:05:24,400 --> 00:05:28,280
but cultivation was just as massive throughout eastern Sicily.

81
00:05:28,280 --> 00:05:32,120
Yet there, the very first Mafia was virtually absent.

82
00:02:09,000 --> 00:05:35,959
The real reason: the two sectors were structurally opposite.

83
00:05:35,959 --> 00:05:41,519
Think about it: sulfur mines were clustered on the surface, very easy to raid,

84
00:05:41,519 --> 00:05:46,800
making intense private armed protection mandatory, especially for escorting transports.

85
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:50,160
The citrus industry, on the contrary, was much more fragmented.

86
00:05:50,160 --> 00:05:53,319
Sure, sometimes the water guards committed extortion,

87
00:05:53,319 --> 00:05:58,519
but more rigorous analyses prove that it was precisely the enormous and lightning-fast economic impact of sulfur

88
00:05:58,519 --> 00:06:00,360
that served as the primary trigger.

89
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:01,759
Part 5.

90
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:04,399
A persistent modern legacy.

91
00:06:04,399 --> 00:06:08,519
Now let's jump from the 19th century to today.

92
00:06:08,519 --> 00:06:10,759
And this is where chills run down your spine,

93
00:06:10,759 --> 00:06:15,519
because the consequences of that historic economic event are sadly still here.

94
00:06:15,519 --> 00:06:19,759
The exact same municipalities that a century ago hosted the sulfur mines

95
00:06:19,759 --> 00:06:22,199
still carry deep scars.

96
00:06:22,199 --> 00:06:24,680
Today, in those specific areas,

97
00:06:24,680 --> 00:06:28,560
we see incredibly higher rates of dissolved city councils,

98
00:06:28,600 --> 00:06:30,759
widespread seizures of local businesses,

99
00:06:30,759 --> 00:06:34,040
and confiscations of property linked to organized crime.

100
00:06:34,040 --> 00:06:37,800
Let that stark statistic sink in for a second:

101
00:06:37,800 --> 00:07:01,360
between 1991 and 2011, more than 10% of all Sicilian municipalities

102
00:06:45,199 --> 00:06:47,879
were dissolved due to Mafia infiltration.

103
00:06:47,879 --> 00:06:51,959
The mathematical connection between those old mines and modern crime

104
00:06:51,959 --> 00:06:54,480
has never really been broken.

105
00:06:54,480 --> 00:06:58,120
And this leaves us with a very powerful final question.

106
00:06:58,160 --> 00:07:01,360
Faced with this incredible persistence in the data,

107
00:07:01,360 --> 00:07:05,000
one wonders if the shadow of a historical economic accident,

108
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,480
of a resource curse triggered centuries ago,

109
00:07:08,480 --> 00:07:10,959
can ever be completely erased.

110
00:07:10,959 --> 00:07:14,360
It makes us understand in an impressive way how geography

111
00:07:14,360 --> 00:07:16,920
and riches arriving suddenly from the past

112
00:07:16,920 --> 00:07:21,519
can deeply shape the very foundations of our modern societies.